    # Indentation in Python:
        # Python does not use curly brackets {} to define code blocks. 
        # Instead, it uses a specific amount of whitespace (1 Tab or 4 Spaces).

        # It is used after keywords like if/else, loops, or functions to show 
        # which lines of code belong to that specific block.

        # If you miss or mess up the spaces, Python will throw an 'IndentationError'.   

    # Quick Example:
        if 5 > 2:
        print("Five is greater than two!") # This indent (space) is mandatory 

