10_Sets:-
    # 1. Sets -> A Set is a collection which is unordered, unchangeable*, and unindexed.Sets do not allow duplicate values. In Python, sets are written with curly brackets {}.

    # Python Set Methods are:
        # union() -> Returns a new set containing all unique elements from both sets.
        # update() -> Adds all elements from another set (or any iterable) to the current set.
        # intersection() -> Returns a new set containing only the common elements.
        # intersection_update() -> Keeps only the common elements in the current set.
        # symmetric_difference() -> Returns a new set containing elements that are in either set, but not in both.
        # difference() -> Returns a new set containing elements that exist in the first set but not in the second set.
        # isdisjoint() -> Returns True if the two sets have no common elements.
        # issuperset() -> Returns True if the current set contains all elements of another set.
        # issubset() -> Returns True if all elements of the current set exist in another set.
        # add() -> Adds a single element to the set.
        # discard() -> Removes the specified element if it exists (does not raise an error if not found).
        # remove() -> Removes the specified element (raises an error if the element is not found).
        # pop() -> Removes and returns a random element from the set.
        # del -> Deletes the entire set.
        # clear() -> Removes all elements from the set, making it empty.















